fields.title: Order Bagels
fields.story: We produce [[units]] kettle-boiled, hand-rolled bagels every other week and deliver them to the Sacramento region on Saturday mornings. Sold in batches of four with the option of adding cream cheese to your order. You choose the toppings. Once we're sold out, that's it for the week!

fields.title: About our Bagels
fields.subtitle: Chasing the NYC flavor and texture!
fields.description: It takes a certain amount of chutzpah to try to deconstruct an iconic food like the bagel. Upon the closure of the Sacramento Bagel Company (2017) and the demolition of the former NY Bagel Boys (2019), we began producing experimental batches of bagels in an attempt to attempt to come as close as possible to a NYC style bagel.

fields.title: Batch Tracking
fields.subtitle: How we track recipe development
fields.description: Each time we make a batch of bagels, we are tracking roughly 30 different variables in the process to attempt to both hone in on the best possible bagel as well as promote consistency between batches. Dough hydration, boil time, alternate ingredient, baking temperatures, kneading and proofing time--all have been tweaked and evaluated over the recipe development period. We continue to monitor and track each batch.

fields.title: Toppings
fields.subtitle: What's a bagel without its toppings?
fields.description: We work with a variety of different traditional bagel toppings: sesame, salt, poppy seed, onion, garlic, and everything. From homemade hickory smoked dried garlic, to pretzel salt which we source from an Mennonite store in Missouri, to Korean black sesame seeds--we're constantly on the search for the perfect toppings for our bagels.

fields.title: Delivery
fields.subtitle: Contactless bagel delivery!
fields.description: Within 10-miles from our house in Tahoe Park, we will deliver directly to your door. Dropping off bagels fresh from our oven with a contact-less delivery. All of our delivery packaging is recyclable (and much is made from 100% recycled materials to start with!)

fields.title: Who we are
fields.Story: Random Bakes started out of a desire to perfect a number of baking recipes coupled with the realization that the running through multiple versions of a recipe led to large piles of baked goods that we then needed to figure out what to do with. Random Bakes is a vehicle to allow us to continue experimenting with recipes and find a way to distribute the resulting baked goods.

fields.title: What is with the name, Random Bakes?
fields.description: On a walk one morning we were discussing the types of projects that we wanted to work on and after listing out a long list of potential items, we realized that we had a long random list of baked goods. Thus Random Bakes was born! We are starting with bagels, but the plan is to offer up a number of random items each week that people can add onto their orders: kettle corn, cupcakes, cookies, et cetera!

fields.title: Keeping things clean
fields.subtitle: Following FDA Best Practices
fields.Story:
We are working to follow the updated FDA BEST Practices for Retail Food Stores, Restaurants, and Food Pick-Up/Delivery Services During the COVID-19 Pandemic. This includes:

  • Self-isolating and suspending operations for two-weeks if there has been any potential exposure to Covid-19.
  • Following FDA guidelines on Food Delivery.
  • Maintaining FDA sanitation and hygiene guidelines.

fields.title: Cottage Food Operation
fields.subtitle: License: PENDING
fields.Story:
Assembly Bill (AB) 1616 authored by Assemblyman Gatto, Chapter 415, Statutes of 2012, was signed into law by Governor Brown on September 21, 2012; effective January 1, 2013. The bill allows individuals to prepare and/or package certain non-potentially hazardous foods in private-home kitchens referred to as cottage food operations (CFOs). All CFOs have to meet specified requirements pursuant to the California Health and Safety Code related to:

  • Preparing foods that are on the approved food list
  • Completing a food processor training course within three months of registering
  • Implementing sanitary operations
  • Establishing state and federal compliant labels
  • Operating within established gross annual sales limits
